Born on May 21, 1844, in Laval, northwest France, Rousseau was the son of a tinsmith and hardware dealer who experienced "bourgeois prosperity" (Shattuck 47). Without any formal artistic training, Rousseau worked until the age of forty in France’s municipal toll service, known as a gabelou, though he was mistakenly referred to as a douanier, or customs inspector (Shattuck 46). The loss of his first wife Clémence, following the deaths of eight infant children, left him with one surviving daughter, Julia, and deep sorrow (Shattuck 49). Seeking solace and a new beginning, Rousseau turned to painting for comfort. Unlike his contemporaries who idealized the peasant life in their art, Rousseau was fundamentally a folk painter with the aspirations common to his social class.

Rousseau’s intense desire for acceptance in the art world is understandable considering his circumstances: he was self-taught, started his artistic career later in life, and was creating art alongside many other renowned modern artists. Despite years of work, Rousseau only began to receive due recognition around the same time Matisse was establishing his reputation. In Modern French Painters, Jan Gordon notes that although Rousseau and Matisse were technically rivals, they differed in style, subject matter, and their motivations for painting: “Matisse feared painting in a clichéd manner, while Rousseau aspired to create art so conventional he would gain entry to the Artiste Français” (92).

Numerous prominent thinkers have suggested a deep link between ethics and aesthetics, as well as between truth and beauty. I think there is a fundamental reason for this connection. As John Keats expresses in “Ode on a Grecian Urn,” “Beauty is truth, truth beauty- That is all / Ye know on earth, and all ye need to know.” Much of our knowledge comes from education or experience, but we seem to appreciate ethics and aesthetics naturally, as Keats hints, without formal teaching. Both ethics and aesthetics aim to describe rather than dictate. Our exploration of morality and beauty primarily seeks to explain why a piece of art or literature is appealing, or why an action is moral, rather than establishing rules for evaluating or creating good art or moral conduct.

Moreover, critiques of art or morals never fully capture the essence of what is good or beautiful. Discussions on the value of da Vinci's Mona Lisa might focus on elements like foreground, background, contrast, or cultural context, but ultimately, these do not explain why it is considered good art. Often, when asked about a favored artwork or literary piece, people might say, “There's just something about it,” before offering a more detailed critique. I believe that art and morals cannot be entirely reduced to their characteristics. As Flannery O'Connor states, “A story is a way to say something that can't be said any other way . . . you tell a story because a statement would be inadequate.” No matter how thoroughly we describe a literary work, something transcendent remains. I think ethics shares this quality. Wittgenstein notes, “It is clear that ethics cannot be expressed. / Ethics is transcendental.” I propose that this “something,” this indefinable quality, is the most compelling aspect of art and morality, and that this transcendental nature provides a connection between them.

I believe the close relationship between morality and art arises because we experience both most profoundly at a noumenal level, to use a Kantian concept. They affect us in ways that can be felt, but not entirely explained. This connection is even more pronounced in literature. As McKean remarks, “What most distinguishes literature from the other arts, what is, in truth, unique about the art, is its moral quality. It may be that moral standards are inappropriate to other arts, music, for instance, but they seem to be as relevant to literature as they are to life itself. Living necessarily involves values. . . . Literature is important to us precisely because of the values we find there.”

Modern Germany is seen as a powerful and unified nation, showcasing a diverse culture that stretches from the Alpine shadows in Munich to the Baltic Sea city of Kiel. This cultural richness extends from Cologne on the Rhine River, through the heart of Germany, to the Saxon city of Dresden on the Elbe. It's not surprising that contemporary Germany's culture stems from various sources and tribes.

The ancestral homeland of the Germans is known as Germania. The name's origin is a subject of debate among scholars and historians. Tacitus suggested it derived from a Germanic tribe called the Tungrians, who were previously known as Germans before crossing the Rhine to confront the Gauls (Tacitus, 98). Julius Caesar first used the term "Germanus" in his commentary on the Gallic Wars, where he subdued the Gauls and clashed with Germanic tribes that frequently crossed the Rhine under dubious motives. He borrowed this term from the Gauls themselves to differentiate between the Gauls he had conquered and the tribes he had not. While the exact origin is uncertain, some believe it referred to a neighboring tribe in the Gaulish language. In the first chapter of his first book on these wars, Caesar mentions: "Germans, who dwell beyond the Rhine, with whom they (The Gauls) are continually waging war.....They contend with the Germans in almost daily battles." (Julius Caesar, 50-40 BC) Others suggest the name could originate from the spear they used in warfare, called a ger (O.E.D, 2010), or perhaps from the Old Irish word garim, meaning "to shout," implying that the Germans were loud or noisy (Names of Germany).

In his AD 98 work "De Origine et situ Germanorum," the early Roman historian Tacitus chronicled the origins of the Germans, asserting, "I should regard (The Germans) as aboriginal, and not mixed at all with other races through immigration or intercourse. For, in former times it was not by land but on shipboard that those who sought to emigrate would arrive.......Who would leave Asia, or Africa, for Italy for Germany, with its wild country, its inclement skies, its sullen manners and aspect, unless indeed it were his home?(SIC)" (Tacitus, 98).

And who would choose to leave Rome for Germania? Certainly not the Romans, at least not initially. They would send expeditions to Germania for goods and occasionally launch land campaigns, but typically they returned to their vast empire. As Germanic tribes began to emerge in the mid-first century, they settled on the Roman Empire's borders, trading goods from the land and serving as skilled soldiers in the Roman army (Ozment, 2005 pg. 17).

In the play Twelfth Night, it suggests that while disguises can be effective tools for sustaining prolonged deception, ultimately, one must abandon these false identities to avoid losing their true selves. However, ending a deception can lead to feelings of alienation. Ultimately, a person must choose between self-preservation and maintaining relationships with those around them. Some may react indifferently upon discovering they've been deceived, while others may take offense at the deception. The issue of deception in gender role reversal brings additional complexities, most notably questioning why someone would feel compelled to abandon their own identity to adopt that of the opposite gender. For Viola, it is clearly a means of self-protection: “I’ll bring you to a captain in this town/ Where lie my maiden weeds, by whose gentle help/ I was preserved to serve this noble count…” (5.1.247-249). Upon arriving in an unfamiliar place, Viola finds it necessary to disguise herself as a man to ensure her safety from potential threats. Her plan succeeds, but it also isolates her from other women, severing her from a crucial support network. Complicating matters further, Viola's male disguise is so convincing that Olivia mistakes her for Sebastian and inadvertently falls in love with her, as shown by Olivia's plea: “Whither, my lord? Cesario, husband, stay.” (5.1.138). Additionally, Viola must navigate her own repressed romantic feelings towards Orsino: “Boy, thou hast said to me a thousand times/ Thou never shouldst love woman like to me.” (5.1.260-261). While this situation might seem progressive, modern readers might view Twelfth Night as a depiction of how deception can uncover hidden emotions, particularly for Olivia and Orsino. Certain sections suggest that these characters might have unspoken desires that Viola/Cesario’s presence compels them to confront. For instance, is Olivia attracted to Cesario because she perceives him as a man, or does she secretly have feelings for women? One might argue against this, as Shakespeare's portrayal of Olivia seems to satirize those of his era who judge others solely on appearance. This is demonstrated by how easily Olivia shifts her romantic interest from Cesario to Sebastian, eventually seeing Cesario/Viola as family rather than a love interest: “A sister, you are she.” (5.1.315).

German colonial rule has been characterized by many as particularly harsh, especially concerning the genocide of the Ovaherero and Nama peoples in what was then German South West Africa. However, it's overly simplistic to describe an entire colonial empire with a single broad stroke. The policies and governance of the German colonial empire were as diverse as the territories it encompassed. Similarly, the educational systems varied across the colonies. When the British assumed control of German East Africa (now Tanganyika) in 1919, they encountered a significant number of educated and literate Africans. German efforts in education within Kamerun and other colonies received commendation from writers of the era. The scenario in South West Africa (modern-day Namibia) was notably different. Unlike East Africa, where the government established state schools and actively participated in educating the local population, in South West Africa, education for the natives was largely left to missionary groups with minimal government assistance. However, the government heavily invested in the education of Europeans in the region, setting up state schools and providing more substantial support and regulation for missionary schools. These policies continued to impact South West Africa long after German rule ended. While other German colonies had significant numbers of literate and educated Africans, in South West Africa, "the overwhelming majority of the population remained untouched, uneducated, and illiterate." Various social, political, and economic factors contributed to the unique circumstances of South West Africa. This paper aims to delve into these factors, with a focus on recent research regarding the perspectives of settlers and colonial authorities towards native Africans. There is an extensive body of literature specifically addressing education in the German colonial empire. Most of these works, written in German during or shortly after the colonial period, aimed to describe the educational systems in these colonies. Later English-language studies expanded the conversation by comparing educational systems across different German colonies and analyzing specific educational aspects in greater detail. These studies highlighted significant differences between the colonies' educational systems. Cohen's work, a prominent study, explicitly addresses the theme of this paper by comparing the educational systems of South West Africa and East Africa and discussing the factors accounting for their differences. According to Cohen, the large European settler population in South West Africa explains many of the unique features of its educational system. Compared to Germany's other colonies, South West Africa had a somewhat temperate climate, despite much of its land being arid desert. The European population reflected these relatively favorable conditions. By 1913, nearly 15,000 Europeans resided in South West Africa, while the next largest settler population was in East Africa, with only 5,336 Europeans.

The United States and Mexico are examples of two countries that experienced a long-standing rivalry lasting 57 years, from 1836 to 1893 (Diehl and Goerts 2000 p. 145). The peak of this conflict was the Mexican-American War from 1846 to 1848, during which the United States attacked and defeated Mexico, gaining Texas and the American Southwest as new territories. Numerous other conflicts occurred between the two nations, eventually subsiding just before World War I. The rivalry was fueled by clashes over key issues such as religion, culture, tradition, and significant material interests (Schmitt 1974 p. 30-31).

This situation is similar to that of many other countries that have enduring rivalries with neighboring nations. Countries that share borders often experience conflicts of interest that lead to rival positions. The United States and Mexico are similar to many enduring rivalries between nations that share a common border. David M. Pletcher (1977) notes that "Only in Mexico and Cuba can one find long-lasting overarching American diplomatic problems" (p. 41). Indeed, both of these countries are geographically close to the United States and have historically been rivals, while other Latin American countries have enjoyed good relations with the U.S.

Religious differences created a division between the two nations, a common issue throughout history. Sally Frahm (2001) notes that "if in the twentieth century Americans were opposed to fascism and communism, in the eighteenth and nineteenth they were opposed to Catholicism and monarchy" (p. 86). Similar to the Cold War rivalry between the United States and the Soviet Union, which was both an ideological struggle and a competition over vital interests, the conflict here was based not on political structures but on religious preferences. This distrust stemmed from historical tensions between the English and Spanish, which were inherited from their former colonial rulers and posed a significant challenge in establishing friendly foreign relations between the United States and Mexico.

Diehl and Goerts (2000) identified 17 disputes between Mexico and the United States during the 57-year rivalry. Most of these disputes, as described by Diehl and Goerts, involved territorial issues, such as border raids from Mexican territory and other frontier problems. Raids by bandits and outlaws into American border towns were a significant issue until both the United States and Mexico used military force to secure their borders (Schmitt 1974 p. 97). Schmitt (1974) explains that the rivalry began to fade as "Mexico became clearly dependent on the United States in a substantial way" (p. 109) and concluded as American ambitions shifted "from territorial expansion to economic intervention into Mexico" (p. 110) in the late 19th century.

Fifteen years ago, I was unexpectedly and suddenly disabled by an illness I had never heard of. At that time, I was a nurse, a career I chose because of a strong desire for the safety and security I lacked during childhood. I often heard the saying, "You'll always find work; people will always get sick," as I grew up. Even though my aspirations were to become a scientist or journalist—or perhaps a bit of both—I opted for nursing.

Nonetheless, there I was at 46 years old, single, with little savings and unable to work. I am still disabled today, and after 15 years of relying on Social Security Disability, I have almost nothing left that I can call my own. I manage to get by, but every day is a challenge, threatening my sense of security, safety, and self-worth. Nothing in my life is predictable anymore, yet one thing remains true: I wouldn't have survived all these years without the support of my family and a few good friends, no matter how strong I believed myself to be. When true disaster hits, you don't feel strong at all.

My point is that emergencies, both big and small, are inevitable in life. There are no guarantees, and despite our best preparations, some challenges are too great to face alone.

I completely agree that in the U.S., we should stop relying solely on big government, which is clearly deteriorating and ineffective. However, I would much prefer to see Americans learning to trust and assist one another and asking for help, rather than each of us individually retreating to build fallout shelters.

Conservatives in the U.S. often speak about the "rugged individualism" that built the nation, but truthfully, what sustained our ancestors during tough times was not rugged individualism but rather compassion, mutual respect, and resource sharing. The pioneers who journeyed across the Rockies in wagon trains didn't make it to the coast by going it alone.

So, definitely be prepared—I am. I have a disaster kit with first aid supplies, water purification tablets, plastic sheeting, and duct tape for windows in case of a biological attack. I own several flashlights, various batteries, plenty of candles, waterproof matches, and canned goods. If you have the land and resources for a small farm and can preserve your own food, go for it. It's an excellent idea, as is having a wood stove, as long as you don't live in an apartment.

But while doing all this, make sure to get to know your neighbors.

Around the fifth or sixth century BCE, a prince was born who would later be known as Buddha. Throughout his life, he gave up worldly possessions, achieved enlightenment, and his teachings laid the groundwork for Buddhism. The most traditional branch of this religion is called Theravada Buddhism. Buddhism has existed for about 2,500 years, and it has evolved since the time of Buddha. This evolution is evident in places like Sri Lanka, a Theravada Buddhist country, where the annual water-cutting ceremony takes place. This ceremony, involving both monks and laypeople, holds religious significance despite not being directly taught by Buddha. Changes in Buddhism range from surface-level traditions to the fundamental beliefs about salvation. Over time, the Theravada Buddhist community, including both monastic and lay members, has had to adapt its principles due to various influences. These influences can be external or internal and can be either harmful or neutral. 

In this discussion, several key terms will be used frequently. "Internal" forces originate within the Buddhist community, regardless of monastic status, while "external" forces come from non-Buddhists. A "hostile" force is one that harms or intends to harm the Buddhist community due to negative views of Buddhism. A "benign" force neither aims to harm nor help the community but may inadvertently do one or the other. These terms will be referenced repeatedly.

Initially, it's crucial to understand the fundamentals of the religion—the core doctrines of Theravada Buddhism. Buddhists seek refuge in the triple gem: the Buddha, the Dhamma, and the Sangha. The Dhamma primarily comprises the Tripitaka, or the three baskets, of Buddhist writings. The Sutta Pitaka contains the discourses, the Vinaya Pitaka outlines the monastic rules, and the Abhidhamma Pitaka includes the philosophical aspects of Buddhism. These philosophical aspects involve concepts like Anatta (no soul), Dukkha (life's inherent suffering), and Anicca (impermanence of all things). By understanding these ideas, one can end Sansara, the cycle of death and rebirth. Enlightenment brings an end to Sansara along with lobha (desire), dosa (hatred), and moha (delusion). The Vinaya Pitaka sets forth rules for life. Laypeople adhere to five precepts: not to kill, lie, steal, engage in sexual misconduct, or take intoxicants. Monks follow many more rules. The fundamental doctrinal concept in Buddhism is the Four Noble Truths: first, the truth that life is suffering (Dukkha); second, that attachment causes suffering; and third, that suffering can be overcome.
